The PF-9 is a semi-automatic, locked breech pistol, chambered for the 9mm Luger cartridge. It has been developed from our highly successful P-11 and P-3AT pistols with maximum concealability in mind. The PF-9 retains the best features from our P-11 and P-3AT pistols combined into the flattest and lightest single stack 9mm configuration ever made. The barrel, locking system, slide stop, assembly pin, front sight, recoil springs and guide rod are adapted from the P-11. The PF-9 is nearly identical to the P-11 in length and height and shares the same exterior controls. The shorter trigger system with integral hammer block and the extraction system are adapted from the P-3AT. Just like the P-11, the PF-9 will accept +P ammunition, however, not with continuous use.

     The rear sight is a new design and is adjustable for windage with the supplied allen wrench as well as for elevation with the use of shims (not included). Armscor/Rock Island M1911-A1 MSP 1911 Midsize GI .45ACP

The Rock Island Armory 1911 series consists of a product line of single-action recoil operated semi-automatic pistols. They are designed and manufactured by Armscor in Marikina City, Philippines, and distributed in the United States by Armscor USA, located in Pahrump, Nevada.

RIA (Rock Island Armory) 1911s are clones of the US Military G.I. M1911-A1, the standard issue US Service pistol from 1911 to 1985. Most RIA models are targeted for the low-end price point of the 1911 pistol market and are basic entry level MIL-SPEC versions of the 1911, however, the RIA Tactical, Compact, and Match models offer additional semi-custom high end features. The Compact model features a skeletonized hammer and beavertail grip safety while the Tactical model also adds a target-grade hammer and trigger as well as an ambidextrous safety, and enhanced contrast combat sights. Armscor is an ISO 9001 certified-compliant company which manufactures Rock Island pistols using CNC (Computer Numerical Control) equipment. RIA 1911 series pistols are constructed of 4140 chromoly steel with a cast frame, and are available in .45 ACP, .38 Super, 9mm Luger, and .22 TCM chamberings.

postcontent: I have decided to sell my HK MR556A1 with Aimpoint PRO. This rifle has a BD date code. For those that don't know, the HK MR556 is a short stroke piston operated rifle built as a civilian version of the 416. The 416 is in use by Marines (IAR27) and by select special forces. It is an outstandingly clean operating system. It also has been upgraded with HK licensed Troy Micro flip-up front and rear sights($190). The sights give absolute 1-1 co-witness to the Aimpoint. It has had the barrel re-profiled to the SOCOM profile by Jayson at IGF. He re-profiles and works on HK's for a living. His work is second to none. It also comes with a 14.5" SS barrel custom made to fit the HK MR556 and 416, it has been Duracoated and includes a BCM flash hider with pin to lengthen it to 16" overall. I bought the barrel for another upper but decided to let it go. The upper has a zero round count, while the lower has a 30 rounds or less count. I used it with my other upper to test the other uppers accuracy. I have a larger trigger guard on it but includes stock flat trigger guard. It has 7 HK High Reliability Magazines (2 I bought used and 5 never fired). It also has 5 HK polymer magazines. It comes with all the paperwork and hard case from HK. I will include the Vickers Padded Combat two point sling with quick release. The Aimpoint PRO is used but in perfect condition with box,spacer (not used as to give co-witness to the HK low profile sights), and paperwork. There is almost $500 worth of magazines at HK's price. The total of the barrel re-profile and nitriding (meloniting) is $340. The extra barrel (new), I put a value of $300 even though it cost more than that to have it made and include an extra barrel nut (not pictured). I also have an HK barrel nut tool that will fit HK's proprietary barrel nut. On a side note the barrel tab was removed by Jayson to allow either the MR556 or 416 BCGs to fit the upper, the 14.5" barrel was made without the tab, so it will work with either also. I honestly am not looking to trade for anything. The only thing I can think I might trade on is partially on a SCAR 17S or DD AR+ cash. title: For Sale:  AR15 80% Forged Lower Cerro Forge
postcontent:
80% Cerro Forge 7075 lower receiver. This is one of the more complete units, as it has the rear takedown pocket machined already. All that is required is purchase of a jig and tooling to finish the fire control pocket and drill for trigger pins and safety. This machining can be done with a drill press, mill, or router, depending on the type of Jig that is purchased. These are available from multiple sources on the internet. 

A word about 80% lowers. The ATF considers an 80% lower as "not a firearm". It is perfectly legal to finish an 80% lower YOURSELF to create a working firearm. The important word here is YOURSELF. With your OWN tools. Read here for a detailed description- 

http://blog.princelaw.com/2015/01/03/atf-issues-first-ruling-of-the-new-year-is-it-the-end-of-80-lowers/

So- please do not ask me if I can finish, help finish, or refer you to someone who can finish this for you. I cannot and will not, as that would be illegal.  I can give you an opinion that these 80% lowers will somehow become legislated out of existence before too long. I'm selling this and the other Billet one listed here because I became interested in other things. Asking $55.00, face to face cash only. Willing to do a bit of a discount if you purchase both.

title: For Sale:  FOR SALE ONLY: ROCK ISLAND 1911 .22 TCM
location: TRI COUNTY, FAIRFIELD, SHARONVILLE, Cincinnati, Ohio
postcontent:
ROCK ISLAND TCM. 22 
COMES WITH EVERYTHING IT CAME WITH NEW.
ALSO COMES WITH TWO BOXES OF .22 TCM THERE IS ONE ROUND MISSING.
Cash only NO TRADES. PRICE IS FIRM. $550.

22 TCM case details
The 22TCM (Tuason Craig Micromagnum)[2] is a proprietary cartridge developed by Fred Craig and Rock Island Armory. Before the cartridge was commercialized, it was called the 22 Micro-Mag. The 22TCM is a bottle necked cartridge referenced as a short 5.56 with performance that exceeds the 5.7x28 FN while being smaller in length and re-loadable. Standard factory loads are 40-grain jacketed soft hollow point. Armscor has announced a new round the 22TCM9R which will be the same case as the 22TCM but have an overall length of the 9mmx19 round. The company plans to release this round in summer of 2015 with a Glock 22TCM9R conversion slide to allow the 22TCM to fit in a 9mm length magazine, hence the "9R" designation. The 22TCM9R will in fact still be a 40GR bullet but will be a fully jacketed hollow point instead.

The 22TCM is based on the 5.56 nato case, shortened so that the shoulder is at approximately the same length as a 38 super cartridge. The cartridge is designed to feed from a Para-Ordnance style double column .38 Super magazine. Currently only Rock Island Armory catalogs firearms chambered in 22TCM: a 1911 style semi-auto pistol (also available with optional additional 9mm barrel and recoil spring), and a bolt action rifle (which reportedly can use the same magazines as the pistols); and only Armscor (the parent company of Rock Island Armory) manufactures ammunition.

80% Billet  lower receiver

-Threaded bolt catch pin (Threaded hole and hardware),

This is one of the more complete units, as it has the rear takedown pocket machined already. All that is required is purchase of a jig and tooling to finish the fire control pocket and drill for trigger pins and safety. This machining can be done with a drill press, mill, or router, depending on the type of Jig that is purchased. These are available from multiple sources on the internet.

A word about 80% lowers. The ATF considers an 80% lower as "not a firearm". It is perfectly legal to finish an 80% lower YOURSELF to create a working firearm. The important word here is YOURSELF. With your OWN tools. Read here for a detailed description-

http://blog.princelaw.com/2015/01/03/atf-issues-first-ruling-of-the-new-year-is-it-the-end-of-80-lowers/

So- please do not ask me if I can finish, help finish, or refer you to someone who can finish this for you. I cannot and will not, as that would be illegal. I can give you an opinion that these 80% lowers will somehow become legislated out of existence before too long. title: For Sale:   1942 Colt M1911 A1 National Match
postcontent:
RARE 1942 Colt M1911 A1 national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1942 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in May of 1942. It is stamped with WB inside a Box for Colonel Waldemar S. Broberg, Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance: July 1, 1941 - June 16, 1942. The WB inspected pistols are a little more rare for that time frame.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by the military, as the barrel has been re-stamped. This gun is in its original time frame finish (parkerized). All Proof markings to fit era. Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. It is amazingly tight and special fitted for accuracy. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

1250$ cash firm.. Thats a fair price, they are going for more than that.. I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. email or text 918-four02-zero854.
